<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-01-24T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-01-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="553" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d553">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72111/4469½</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-01-24">
                                    <hi rend="italic">24 January, 1917</hi>.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: It is only too probable
                            that Gerard’s conjectures in this matter are well founded. I wonder if
                            you have come to any fixed conclusion in your own mind as to whether the
                            recent practices of the British in regard to the arming of their
                            merchantmen force upon us an alteration of our own position in that
                            matter.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>W. W.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>